          "id": "business-ethics-301-l02-c1",
          "title": "The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)",
          "content": "The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, commonly known as the FCPA, was established in 1977 with the important goal of ensuring that U.S. individuals and businesses do not engage in bribery of foreign government officials. This law is crucial for promoting fair business practices globally. The FCPA consists of two main components that work together to uphold ethical standards in international business.\nFirstly, the anti-bribery provision explicitly prohibits any corrupt payments made to foreign officials with the intention of obtaining or retaining business advantages. This means that it is illegal for U.S. companies or individuals to offer money or gifts to foreign officials in exchange for favorable treatment or contracts. Such actions not only undermine fair competition but also damage the integrity of global business relations.\nSecondly, the accounting provision requires companies to maintain accurate financial records and implement effective internal controls. This ensures that all transactions are properly documented and that there is transparency in financial dealings. By adhering to these accounting standards, companies can prevent fraudulent activities and promote accountability within their operations.\nThe FCPA is applicable not only to U.S. companies but also extends to their subsidiaries and foreign companies that are listed on U.S. stock exchanges. This broad scope emphasizes the importance of ethical conduct in business, regardless of where the company operates.\nViolating the FCPA can result in severe consequences. Individuals found guilty of breaching this law may face fines of up to $250,000, while companies can incur penalties of up to $2 million for each violation. Additionally, individuals may face imprisonment for up to five years. These strict penalties highlight the seriousness of adhering to ethical business practices and the commitment to combating corruption on a global scale.\nContext recap: The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, commonly known as the FCPA, was established in 1977 with the important goal of ensuring that U.S. individuals and businesses do not engage in bribery of foreign government officials. This law is crucial for promoting fair business practices globally. The FCPA consists of two main components that work together to uphold ethical standards in international business.\nWhy this matters: The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) helps learners in Business connect ideas from Ethics in Global Business to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
