          "content": "The UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, created in 2011 by John Ruggie, provide an important framework known as 'Protect, Respect, and Remedy.' This framework highlights the essential roles that both governments and businesses play in upholding human rights. Firstly, it is the responsibility of states to protect human rights, ensuring that all individuals are treated fairly and with dignity. On the other hand, businesses have a crucial obligation to respect these rights. This means they must take proactive steps to avoid causing harm and must also address any negative impacts that their operations might have on individuals and communities. Furthermore, it is vital that those who suffer from human rights violations have access to effective remedies, allowing them to seek justice and support. To meet their responsibility of respecting human rights, companies must engage in a process called due diligence. This involves carefully assessing both the actual and potential impacts of their activities on human rights. Companies should integrate the findings from these assessments into their everyday business practices, continuously monitor how effective their actions are, and clearly communicate how they are addressing any impacts they identify. By doing so, businesses can contribute to a more just and equitable world, ensuring that human rights are upheld in every aspect of their operations.\nContext recap: The UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, created in 2011 by John Ruggie, provide an important framework known as 'Protect, Respect, and Remedy.' This framework highlights the essential roles that both governments and businesses play in upholding human rights. Firstly, it is the responsibility of states to protect human rights, ensuring that all individuals are treated fairly and with dignity. On the other hand, businesses have a crucial obligation to respect these rights. This means they must take proactive steps to avoid causing harm and must also address any negative impacts that their operations might have on individuals and communities.\nWhy this matters: UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights helps learners in Business connect ideas from Ethics in Global Business to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
