          "id": "business-ethics-301-l04-c1",
          "title": "Environmental Ethics in Business",
          "content": "Environmental ethics is a fascinating field that explores how humans relate to the natural world around us. When we think about businesses, this raises some really important questions. For instance, do companies have responsibilities that go beyond just following the law when it comes to protecting our environment? Should they think about how their actions today will affect future generations? There are three main viewpoints that help us understand these questions better. The first is called anthropocentrism, which means that nature is valued mainly for how it benefits humans. The second viewpoint is biocentrism, which believes that all living beings have moral worth and deserve consideration. Finally, we have ecocentrism, which takes a broader approach by valuing entire ecosystems and the natural processes that keep them healthy. Many businesses today try to combine ideas from both anthropocentric and ecocentric perspectives when they think about their responsibilities towards the environment. This blending of ideas helps companies make more thoughtful decisions that can benefit both people and the planet. Understanding these perspectives is crucial for anyone interested in how businesses can operate ethically in a world that needs protection and care for its natural resources.\nContext recap: Environmental ethics is a fascinating field that explores how humans relate to the natural world around us. When we think about businesses, this raises some really important questions. For instance, do companies have responsibilities that go beyond just following the law when it comes to protecting our environment? Should they think about how their actions today will affect future generations?\nWhy this matters: Environmental Ethics in Business helps learners in Business connect ideas from Ethics in Global Business to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
